## PART 2: What Changes Given These Architectural Choices

### 2.1 DI: swift-dependencies Replaces Factory Protocols

**What I originally proposed:** Factory protocols + composition root with `lazy var` properties.

**What changes:** `@DependencyClient` structs with closure-based APIs, `@Dependency` property wrapper for access, `withDependencies {}` for testing.

**Concrete migration from current Swinject:**

Current pattern (7 Assembly files, ~8 `import Swinject` files):
```swift
// Current: Swinject registration
container.register(AuthRepository.self) { r in
    AuthRepositoryImpl(
        alphaPointService: r.resolve(AlphaPointServiceProtocol.self)!,
        webSocketService: r.resolve(WebSocketServiceProtocol.self)!
    )
}.inObjectScope(.transient)
```

New pattern:
```swift
// NetworkKit/AlphaPointClient.swift
@DependencyClient
struct AlphaPointClient {
    var login: @Sendable (_ credentialBase64: String) async throws -> AuthResult
    var getAccountPositions: @Sendable (_ accountId: Int) async throws -> [AccountPosition]
    var getInstruments: @Sendable () async throws -> [InstrumentDTO]
    var sendOrder: @Sendable (_ order: OrderRequest) async throws -> OrderResponse
}

extension AlphaPointClient: DependencyKey {
    static let liveValue = AlphaPointClient(
        login: { credential in
            // Alamofire call
        },
        getAccountPositions: { accountId in
            // ...
        },
        // ...
    )

    static let testValue = AlphaPointClient()  // All closures unimplemented by default
}

extension DependencyValues {
    var alphaPointClient: AlphaPointClient {
        get { self[AlphaPointClient.self] }
        set { self[AlphaPointClient.self] = newValue }
    }
}
```

**Key mapping for current services:**

| Current Swinject Service | New @DependencyClient |
|-------------------------|----------------------|
| `AlphaPointServiceProtocol` | `AlphaPointClient` |
| `BitazzaApiServiceProtocol` | `BitazzaAPIClient` |
| `BitazzaGatewayServiceProtocol` | `BitazzaGatewayClient` |
| `PublicServiceProtocol` | `PublicAPIClient` |
| `ActivityServiceProtocol` | `ActivityClient` |
| `WebSocketServiceProtocol` | `WebSocketClient` (struct of closures) |
| `AuthRepository` | Inline into relevant clients or thin use-case structs |
| `InstrumentRepository` | `InstrumentClient` or inline in DomainKit |

**Critical concern -- WSNetworkerFactory:**
The current WebSocket has a dual-mode factory (live vs simulator) registered via named Swinject registrations. With swift-dependencies, this becomes:

```swift
@DependencyClient
struct WebSocketClient {
    var connect: @Sendable () async -> Void
    var disconnect: @Sendable () async -> Void
    var connectionStatus: @Sendable () -> AsyncStream<Bool>
    var subscribeLevel1: @Sendable (_ instrumentId: Int) -> AsyncThrowingStream<Level1Summary, Error>
    var subscribeLevel2: @Sendable (_ instrumentId: Int) -> AsyncThrowingStream<[OrderBook], Error>
    var unsubscribeLevel2: @Sendable (_ instrumentId: Int) async throws -> Void
    var authenticate: @Sendable (_ apiKey: String, _ nonce: String, _ signature: String, _ userId: String) async throws -> AuthResult
}

// The live/simulator switching happens at the liveValue level:
extension WebSocketClient: DependencyKey {
    static let liveValue: WebSocketClient = {
        let factory = WSNetworkerFactory(
            liveNetworker: WSNetworker(url: AppConstants.WEBSOCKET_URL),
            simulatorNetworker: WSNetworker(url: AppConstants.SIMULATOR_WEBSOCKET_URL)
        )
        return WebSocketClient(
            connect: { await factory.currentNetworker().connect() },
            // ... closures delegate to factory
        )
    }()
}
```

